like Raymond Chandler
and Salinger

257
00:19:15,220 --> 00:19:17,656
whose books
I devoured.

258
00:19:39,545 --> 00:19:41,580
( thud )

259
00:19:46,818 --> 00:19:49,354
( creaking )

260
00:19:53,625 --> 00:19:55,661
Doris?

261
00:20:05,971 --> 00:20:08,407
Hi.

262
00:20:09,908 --> 00:20:12,444
Hello.

263
00:20:12,477 --> 00:20:15,747
I am terribly sorry.
I thought it was Doris.

264
00:20:15,781 --> 00:20:17,749
You're foreign,
aren't you?

265
00:20:17,783 --> 00:20:20,152
You're not
an ordinary student.

266
00:20:20,185 --> 00:20:23,288
Is my accent that bad?

267
00:20:23,322 --> 00:20:24,623
No.

268
00:20:29,928 --> 00:20:33,232
I can tell by the fact
that you can look me
in the eyes.

269
00:20:33,265 --> 00:20:37,069
American boys
can't seem to look
Negro girls in the eyes.

270
00:20:39,338 --> 00:20:41,773
Do you want
some coffee?

271
00:20:41,807 --> 00:20:44,476
Yes, please.

272
00:20:46,912 --> 00:20:49,414
What's your name?

273
00:20:49,448 --> 00:20:51,483
Philippe.

274
00:20:53,285 --> 00:20:55,254
Philippe.

275
00:20:55,287 --> 00:20:57,889
Philippe's voice:
Suddenly I realized
that I hadn't heard

276
00:20:57,923 --> 00:20:59,558
my own name
in months.

277
00:20:59,591 --> 00:21:01,860
I hadn't been Philippe
since I left Paris.

278
00:21:01,893 --> 00:21:03,862
Careful.
It's hot.

279
00:21:03,895 --> 00:21:06,331
You like this book?

280
00:21:06,365 --> 00:21:08,333
I don't know.

281
00:21:08,367 --> 00:21:11,737
I am only
on page two.

282
00:21:11,770 --> 00:21:13,739
Have you read it?

283
00:21:13,772 --> 00:21:16,308
Read it and taught it.
I don't just clean houses.

284
00:21:16,341 --> 00:21:18,910
I'm a teacher.

285
00:21:18,944 --> 00:21:20,912
- At college?
- No.

286
00:21:20,946 --> 00:21:25,183
I teach elementary school
on the other side of town.

287
00:21:25,217 --> 00:21:27,185
But now I have to go.

288
00:21:27,219 --> 00:21:30,956
No, please,
five more minutes.

289
00:21:30,989 --> 00:21:34,459
Non, Philippe,
ce n'est pas possible.

290
00:21:34,493 --> 00:21:36,928
Vous parlez Francais?

291
00:21:36,962 --> 00:21:38,930
Well, through the mail.

292
00:21:38,964 --> 00:21:42,167
I took this
correspondence course.

293
00:21:42,200 --> 00:21:44,303
But now I have to go.

294
00:21:44,336 --> 00:21:47,739
No, stay
for just a moment.

295
00:21:49,675 --> 00:21:51,877
Say my name again.

296
00:21:51,910 --> 00:21:54,513
Please.

297
00:21:54,546 --> 00:21:56,782
Why should I say
your name?

298
00:21:56,815 --> 00:22:00,719
Because nobody calls me
by my real name.

299
00:22:00,752 --> 00:22:03,955
And when you say it

300
00:22:03,989 --> 00:22:07,059
it makes me feel
less lonely.

301
00:22:07,092 --> 00:22:09,594
Are you lonely,

302
00:22:09,628 --> 00:22:12,397
Philippe?

303
00:22:12,431 --> 00:22:16,001
Sometimes.

304
00:22:16,034 --> 00:22:19,037
Are you lonely now?

305
00:22:19,071 --> 00:22:21,239
No.

306
00:22:31,883 --> 00:22:34,453
What's your name?

307
00:22:34,486 --> 00:22:36,655
April.

308
00:22:57,776 --> 00:22:59,745
Hey, kid.

309
00:22:59,778 --> 00:23:02,080
I'm glad
you're still here.

310
00:23:02,114 --> 00:23:06,518
So how are you cottoning
to old JD there?

311
00:23:06,551 --> 00:23:08,520
I am in love.

312
00:23:08,553 --> 00:23:11,456
I know what you mean.
Wait till you get
to the part

313
00:23:11,490 --> 00:23:13,325
where he dreams
of catching the boys.

314
00:23:13,358 --> 00:23:16,061
No no, with a girl.

315
00:23:18,430 --> 00:23:21,032
Oh, well,
that's great, kid.

316
00:23:21,066 --> 00:23:23,068
Do I know her?

317
00:23:23,101 --> 00:23:25,904
No, I don't think so.

318
00:23:25,937 --> 00:23:27,739
I'm afraid
I have to go.

319
00:23:31,143 --> 00:23:33,111
I have class at noon.

320
00:23:33,145 --> 00:23:35,547
Well, take the book,
junior--

321
00:23:35,580 --> 00:23:38,784
the least I can do.

322
00:23:38,817 --> 00:23:40,786
Thank you.
You did a lot.

323
00:23:40,819 --> 00:23:43,722
Careful now.
Don't let those
Southern belles

324
00:23:43,755 --> 00:23:45,891
spin your head
around.

325
00:23:45,924 --> 00:23:48,527
I won't.

326
00:23:51,163 --> 00:23:53,765
( boys chattering )

327
00:23:57,135 --> 00:23:59,204
- Hey, Frenchy.
- Hello.

328
00:23:59,237 --> 00:24:02,240
Merci beaucoup.
( laughing )

329
00:24:02,274 --> 00:24:04,609
( dance music playing )

330
00:24:08,814 --> 00:24:10,782
Have you seen
Cal around?

331
00:24:10,816 --> 00:24:12,617
Cal?
Cal who?

332
00:24:12,651 --> 00:24:14,519
Please.
Cal Cate.

333
00:24:14,553 --> 00:24:16,555
He's over there
watching TV.

334
00:24:25,163 --> 00:24:26,898
Cal, can I borrow
your car?

335
00:24:26,932 --> 00:24:28,900
Are you kidding me?

336
00:24:28,934 --> 00:24:30,902
That's a big favor,
Greenhorn.

337
00:24:30,936 --> 00:24:33,605
It needs a big trade.

338
00:24:33,638 --> 00:24:36,741
You have a French exam
coming up, don't you?

339
00:24:36,775 --> 00:24:39,144
- Can you
guarantee me an A?
- Of course.

340
00:24:39,177 --> 00:24:41,646
- You got a license?
- I have everything--

341
00:24:41,680 --> 00:24:44,182
a license, money,
insurance.

342
00:24:44,216 --> 00:24:48,453
One scratch and I'll
pay you 1000 times.

343
00:24:48,487 --> 00:24:51,790
Oh, Frenchy, Frenchy.

344
00:24:54,559 --> 00:24:57,162
Boy, you are lying
when you're lying.

345
00:24:57,195 --> 00:25:00,031
But if you want
I'll take you where
you need to go.

346
00:25:05,737 --> 00:25:08,139
So, pard, is this
just a joy ride

347
00:25:08,173 --> 00:25:10,141
or you actually want
to go someplace?

348
00:25:10,175 --> 00:25:12,844
I want to go where
the black people live.

349
00:25:12,878 --> 00:25:15,380
No shit!

350
00:25:15,413 --> 00:25:17,382
Frenchy wants to go
to nigger town.

351
00:25:17,415 --> 00:25:19,885
What did you do, boy,
go and get yourself
some whore?

352
00:25:19,918 --> 00:25:21,887
She's not a whore.

353
00:25:21,920 --> 00:25:24,322
Her name is April.

354
00:25:24,356 --> 00:25:26,658
Look, just tell me
where it is and I'll walk.

355
00:25:26,691 --> 00:25:29,127
Oh, okay, now he's gonna
walk in the nigger town.

356
00:25:29,160 --> 00:25:31,596
Boy, they'll take
them straight razors

357
00:25:31,630 --> 00:25:34,232
and cut your French ass
to ribbons.

358
00:25:34,266 --> 00:25:36,334
No, me Southern
gentleman,

359
00:25:36,368 --> 00:25:38,270
me keep his word.

360
00:25:38,303 --> 00:25:39,971
But I don't have
to like it.

361
00:25:43,341 --> 00:25:45,744
( people chattering )

362
00:25:48,246 --> 00:25:50,615
( baby crying )

363
00:25:56,354 --> 00:25:59,257
I don't suppose
we got an address
on this maid, huh?

364
00:25:59,291 --> 00:26:01,927
April.

365
00:26:01,960 --> 00:26:03,962
No.

366
00:26:08,500 --> 00:26:10,468
She teaches school.

367
00:26:10,502 --> 00:26:13,138
Not at this hour,
she don't.

368
00:26:18,543 --> 00:26:22,314
I'll tell you what--
I know the Cates
rode with Lee.

369
00:26:22,347 --> 00:26:24,816
If I had a couple of boys
like this on my team--

370
00:26:24,849 --> 00:26:27,385
take conference
every year.

371
00:26:27,419 --> 00:26:30,088
Why don't you
ask the coach?

372
00:26:30,121 --> 00:26:32,357
Yeah, sure,
the day it rains beer.

373
00:26:32,390 --> 00:26:34,593
Look, let's just get
the hell out of here,
all right?

374
00:26:34,626 --> 00:26:36,895
No, please,

375
00:26:36,928 --> 00:26:39,064
another five minutes.

376
00:26:41,700 --> 00:26:44,035
All right,
you said she was
a school teacher, right?

377
00:26:44,069 --> 00:26:45,804
Let's go to the church.

378
00:26:45,837 --> 00:26:48,173
They'll know
where to find her.

379
00:26:48,206 --> 00:26:50,208
( dogs barking )

380
00:27:04,289 --> 00:27:06,257
Philippe's voice:
There are two hearts

381
00:27:06,291 --> 00:27:08,393
that beat
in the body of America.

382
00:27:08,426 --> 00:27:11,396
One is hidden
behind the other.

383
00:27:11,429 --> 00:27:14,165
And once
I heard its cry,

384
00:27:14,199 --> 00:27:16,368
nothing was ever
quite the same for me.

385
00:27:16,401 --> 00:27:18,203
( people singing psalm )

386
00:27:18,236 --> 00:27:19,938
All right, Hoss,
last chance.

387
00:27:19,971 --> 00:27:21,973
Big Cal needs
his sleep.

388
00:27:32,417 --> 00:27:35,820
♪ ...Just to know ♪

389
00:27:35,854 --> 00:27:40,392
♪ Thus saith the Lord ♪

390
00:27:40,425 --> 00:27:44,496
♪ 'Tis so sweet ♪

391
00:27:44,529 --> 00:27:49,134
♪ To trust in Jesus ♪

392
00:27:49,167 --> 00:27:53,405
♪ Just to take Him ♪

393
00:27:53,438 --> 00:27:57,442
♪ At His word ♪

394
00:27:57,475 --> 00:28:01,513
♪ Just to rest... ♪

395
00:28:01,546 --> 00:28:05,283
Philippe,
what in God's name
are you doing here?

396
00:28:05,316 --> 00:28:08,086
Looking for you.

397
00:28:08,119 --> 00:28:11,122
Children, I know
God is love,

398
00:28:11,156 --> 00:28:13,525
but you'd better
take this outside.

399
00:28:13,558 --> 00:28:17,696
♪ ...Just to know ♪

400
00:28:17,729 --> 00:28:22,200
♪ Thus saith the Lord... ♪

401
00:28:22,233 --> 00:28:24,536
( door creaks )

402
00:28:28,840 --> 00:28:32,477
How did you know
how to find me?

403
00:28:32,510 --> 00:28:36,014
Inspiration.

404
00:28:36,047 --> 00:28:39,484
Okay, Philippe,
what do you want?

405
00:28:39,517 --> 00:28:42,020
I must see you again.

406
00:28:42,053 --> 00:28:44,522
Otherwise I will die.

407
00:28:44,556 --> 00:28:47,392
Well, we can't have
that now, can we?

408
00:28:47,425 --> 00:28:50,495
No, my parents
will be very sad.

409
00:28:52,263 --> 00:28:54,866
Give me one good reason
why I should see you.

410
00:28:54,899 --> 00:28:57,335
Because...

411
00:28:58,770 --> 00:29:01,106
I think sometimes
you must be lonely too.

412
00:29:02,941 --> 00:29:06,244
And of course

413
00:29:06,277 --> 00:29:08,646
I can give you
French lessons.

414
00:29:10,815 --> 00:29:13,685
All right.

415
00:29:13,718 --> 00:29:15,954
You be here
the day after tomorrow.

416
00:29:17,355 --> 00:29:19,190
4:00.

417
00:29:30,401 --> 00:29:32,370
Well, I got to say
one thing, Phil--

418
00:29:32,403 --> 00:29:34,372
if you're gonna
risk your neck
for a colored girl,

419
00:29:34,405 --> 00:29:36,174
it might as well
be her.

420
00:29:36,207 --> 00:29:38,176
Isn't she beautiful?

421
00:29:38,209 --> 00:29:40,512
Isn't she
the most beautiful girl
you've ever seen?

422
00:29:40,545 --> 00:29:42,113
Sure she is, Hoss.

423
00:29:42,147 --> 00:29:44,516
I mean, she's
really something.

424
00:29:44,549 --> 00:29:47,819
And so are you,
so just be careful.

425
00:29:47,852 --> 00:29:51,322
Why? Why is everybody
warning me?

426
00:29:51,356 --> 00:29:53,224
Because we're
from the South.

427
00:29:53,258 --> 00:29:55,627
What do you see
that's so bad?

428
00:29:55,660 --> 00:29:57,362
Nothing.

429
00:29:57,395 --> 00:29:59,364
I mean, hey, if she's
your one and only,

430
00:29:59,397 --> 00:30:01,833
maybe God will
protect y'all.

431
00:30:01,866 --> 00:30:03,835
But there's just
one thing, Phil,

432
00:30:03,868 --> 00:30:05,837
and this is
real important--

433
00:30:05,870 --> 00:30:08,339
hey, you don't
breathe a word

434
00:30:08,373 --> 00:30:10,341
of this
affair of the heart
to anyone.

435
00:30:10,375 --> 00:30:12,911
You understand?

436
00:30:12,944 --> 00:30:15,613
Okay?
Or we're all dead.

437
00:30:15,647 --> 00:30:18,116
Philippe's voice:
My favorite teacher
was a man

438
00:30:18,149 --> 00:30:21,953
with the improbable name
of Zachariah Wilhelm Gilmore,

439
00:30:21,986 --> 00:30:25,156
the Liberal Arts Dean
and the living legend.

440
00:30:25,190 --> 00:30:27,158
During the war

441
00:30:27,192 --> 00:30:29,160
he had worked
under Wild Bill Donovan,

442
00:30:29,194 --> 00:30:31,162
the founder of the CIA,

443
00:30:31,196 --> 00:30:33,164
and returned
to the Shenandoah Valley

444
00:30:33,198 --> 00:30:36,701
with a chestful of medals
and his reputation made.

445
00:30:36,734 --> 00:30:40,405
We called him Zach.

446
00:30:40,438 --> 00:30:45,076
Now some poets,
ladies and gentlemen,

447
00:30:45,109 --> 00:30:49,948
turn their lives
into their great poems.

448
00:30:49,981 --> 00:30:53,751
Do any examples spring
to your eager minds?

449
00:30:55,486 --> 00:30:59,023
The dreamy-eyed
Monsieur Leclerc?

450
00:31:01,993 --> 00:31:05,230
Byron, sir?

451
00:31:05,263 --> 00:31:08,199
Byron.
Byron!

452
00:31:08,233 --> 00:31:10,602
He had to mention Byron,

453
00:31:10,635 --> 00:31:13,504
the one man
who confounds us all.

454
00:31:13,538 --> 00:31:16,074
But why don't we
mention Bulgakov,

455
00:31:16,107 --> 00:31:18,576
who had to share
his mistress with Stalin

456
00:31:18,610 --> 00:31:21,012
so he could write
the "Master and Margarita"

457
00:31:21,045 --> 00:31:25,149
while locked
in a duel to the death
with morphine?

458
00:31:25,183 --> 00:31:27,185
Or Harry Crosby

459
00:31:27,218 --> 00:31:30,889
or Monsieur Rimbaud?

460
00:31:33,024 --> 00:31:36,027
You mentioned
Harry Crosby, sir.

461
00:31:36,060 --> 00:31:38,329
I'm not familiar
with that name.

462
00:31:38,363 --> 00:31:41,099
Harry?

463
00:31:43,067 --> 00:31:45,036
Crosby was a Brahmin,

464
00:31:45,069 --> 00:31:48,706
a Boston Brahmin,
nephew of Pierpont Morgan

465
00:31:48,740 --> 00:31:51,009
and a true decadent.

466
00:31:51,042 --> 00:31:53,778
He lived
in your city, Philippe,

467
00:31:53,811 --> 00:31:57,215
died in the arms
of his mistress,

468
00:31:57,248 --> 00:32:00,118
the Fire Princess,

469
00:32:00,151 --> 00:32:04,222
at the Hotel Des Artistes
in New York City,

470
00:32:04,255 --> 00:32:06,224
a double suicide.

471
00:32:06,257 --> 00:32:08,860
On the sole
of his left foot

472
00:32:08,893 --> 00:32:10,862
they found a tattoo

473
00:32:10,895 --> 00:32:14,632
of our Savior Jesus Christ
on the cross.

474
00:32:18,069 --> 00:32:23,007
So if any of you feel

475
00:32:23,041 --> 00:32:26,177
as if you are
a decadent,

476
00:32:26,210 --> 00:32:28,980
as some of our young
Southern gentlemen

477
00:32:29,013 --> 00:32:30,982
are wont to do,

478
00:32:31,015 --> 00:32:33,651
feeling the weight
of their bloodlines,

479
00:32:33,685 --> 00:32:36,654
you all have
a long way to go.

480
00:32:48,967 --> 00:32:51,269
What are you still
doing here,

481
00:32:51,302 --> 00:32:53,838
you dwarves,
you dreadful

482
00:32:53,871 --> 00:32:56,941
onanistic
small-timers?

483
00:32:56,975 --> 00:32:58,943
Can't you see
that I am walking

484
00:32:58,977 --> 00:33:01,312
with the ghosts
of the great?

485
00:33:11,489 --> 00:33:14,459
Philippe's voice:
French was the bridge

486
00:33:14,492 --> 00:33:17,729
on which
April and I met.

487
00:33:17,762 --> 00:33:20,965
In many ways she was
even more of an outsider
than me

488
00:33:20,999 --> 00:33:24,502
because I could at least
go back to Paris,

489
00:33:24,535 --> 00:33:26,504
but where was she
going to go

490
00:33:26,537 --> 00:33:28,940
with her books,
her correspondence courses

491
00:33:28,973 --> 00:33:31,275
and her dreams

492
00:33:31,309 --> 00:33:34,879
except to a country
that hadn't yet been made

493
00:33:34,912 --> 00:33:37,715
and is even today
far from finished?

494
00:33:39,017 --> 00:33:43,254
Take aimer--

495
00:33:43,287 --> 00:33:46,557
"to love."

496
00:33:46,591 --> 00:33:49,193
Plus-que-parfait--

497
00:33:49,227 --> 00:33:50,962
j'avais aimé.

498
00:33:50,995 --> 00:33:53,798
I had loved?

499
00:33:53,831 --> 00:33:56,667
Exactly.

500
00:34:03,775 --> 00:34:07,545
And now for
the conditionnel passé.

501
00:34:11,449 --> 00:34:13,918
J'aurais aimé.

502
00:34:13,951 --> 00:34:16,320
I would have loved?

503
00:34:21,325 --> 00:34:23,294
Oui.

504
00:34:23,327 --> 00:34:25,730
J'aurais aimé Philippe,

505
00:34:25,763 --> 00:34:28,032
but all we did
was study French.

506
00:34:28,066 --> 00:34:30,435
What else
did you have in mind?

507
00:34:30,468 --> 00:34:33,137
I don't know.

508
00:34:33,171 --> 00:34:35,139
I'm very surprised
some Southern belle

509
00:34:35,173 --> 00:34:37,875
hasn't thrown herself
into your arms.

510
00:34:37,909 --> 00:34:39,877
They run from me.

511
00:34:39,911 --> 00:34:42,280
You're meant to chase them.

512
00:34:42,313 --> 00:34:44,749
I only want
to chase you.

513
00:34:46,350 --> 00:34:48,386
So chase me.

514
00:35:02,900 --> 00:35:05,303
( laughs )

515
00:35:05,336 --> 00:35:08,239
What?
What?

516
00:35:08,272 --> 00:35:10,675
Why are you laughing?

517
00:35:10,708 --> 00:35:13,144
How long
have you been driving?

518
00:35:13,177 --> 00:35:15,446
Since this afternoon.

519
00:35:15,480 --> 00:35:17,281
Cal is playing
Clemson.

520
00:35:17,315 --> 00:35:19,117
He won't be back
