00:52:30,046 --> 00:52:33,183
I only love you.

781
00:52:33,216 --> 00:52:37,687
For you
I'll risk everything.

782
00:52:37,721 --> 00:52:40,056
Can't you see that,

783
00:52:40,090 --> 00:52:42,058
ma petite reine?

784
00:52:42,092 --> 00:52:44,361
I'm your little queen?

785
00:52:44,394 --> 00:52:46,429
Yes.

786
00:52:48,565 --> 00:52:51,601
You're the queen
of my heart.

787
00:52:51,635 --> 00:52:53,837
I'm going to take you
to Paris

788
00:52:53,870 --> 00:52:55,839
where things
are different.

789
00:52:55,872 --> 00:52:58,375
And we'll marry.

790
00:53:05,048 --> 00:53:07,784
That's nonsense.
It's never gonna happen.

791
00:53:11,988 --> 00:53:14,658
I like you.

792
00:53:14,691 --> 00:53:18,195
You're different.

793
00:53:18,228 --> 00:53:22,165
I like the way you talk

794
00:53:22,199 --> 00:53:25,769
and you're gentle,
but it's all it is.

795
00:53:25,802 --> 00:53:28,138
It's all it's ever
gonna be.

796
00:53:28,171 --> 00:53:31,341
You and I come from
very different worlds.

797
00:53:32,976 --> 00:53:35,545
No.

798
00:53:35,579 --> 00:53:40,050
You and I-- we are
from the same world.

799
00:53:40,083 --> 00:53:44,221
The wind blows
in our face the same way.

800
00:53:44,254 --> 00:53:46,623
And the sun shines

801
00:53:46,656 --> 00:53:50,327
in your face and in my face
the same way.

802
00:53:50,360 --> 00:53:54,664
The rain
makes us both wet.

803
00:53:54,698 --> 00:53:56,666
You are not from Mars

804
00:53:56,700 --> 00:54:00,270
and I'm not from the moon.

805
00:54:00,303 --> 00:54:04,441
Say my name in French.

806
00:54:04,474 --> 00:54:06,443
Avril,

807
00:54:06,476 --> 00:54:08,511
mon coeur.

808
00:54:31,868 --> 00:54:33,903
Mr. Leclerc.

809
00:54:35,572 --> 00:54:37,574
Mr. Leclerc.

810
00:54:39,042 --> 00:54:41,578
Mr. Leclerc,
I have decided

811
00:54:41,611 --> 00:54:44,381
for the sake of my garden
and for my own mental health

812
00:54:44,414 --> 00:54:46,850
to find another
assignment for you

813
00:54:46,883 --> 00:54:48,852
more in keeping
with your talents,

814
00:54:48,885 --> 00:54:51,388
meager though
they might be.

815
00:54:55,892 --> 00:54:58,461
( all chattering,
crowd cheering )

816
00:55:08,305 --> 00:55:09,606
( groans )

817
00:55:12,008 --> 00:55:14,577
My leg, man.
I can't-- I can't--

818
00:55:14,611 --> 00:55:16,646
All right, come on.

819
00:55:23,953 --> 00:55:27,190
Coach:
Straighten out.
Straighten out there.

820
00:55:27,223 --> 00:55:30,126
Hi, Cal.
Great game.

821
00:55:31,761 --> 00:55:34,230
Yeah, sure.

822
00:55:34,264 --> 00:55:36,232
What's the matter
with your kicker?

823
00:55:36,266 --> 00:55:39,069
The asshole tried
to kick the ball
out of the stadium.

824
00:55:39,102 --> 00:55:41,805
Now he's got
a groin pull.

825
00:55:41,838 --> 00:55:44,641
What's a groin pull?

826
00:55:44,674 --> 00:55:47,043
It's exactly what
it sounds like, Phil.

827
00:55:47,077 --> 00:55:50,347
It means he's out
for the season.

828
00:55:54,584 --> 00:55:57,554
All right, look,

829
00:55:57,587 --> 00:55:59,556
next week we got
our biggest game,

830
00:55:59,589 --> 00:56:01,491
Alabama Tech, okay?

831
00:56:01,524 --> 00:56:03,493
I mean, their defense
is good--

832
00:56:03,526 --> 00:56:05,895
really good.
You hear me talking?

833
00:56:05,929 --> 00:56:08,498
It means I can't get 'em
in the end zone,

834
00:56:08,531 --> 00:56:13,002
it's gonna come down
to a field goal again.

835
00:56:13,036 --> 00:56:15,004
We're gonna be trying out
kickers all week.

836
00:56:15,038 --> 00:56:17,073
It's gonna be
a nightmare.

837
00:56:23,980 --> 00:56:26,816
Oh, I see that Faulkner
is lecturing

838
00:56:26,850 --> 00:56:28,885
at Washington and Lee.

839
00:56:28,918 --> 00:56:30,887
- Are you interested?
- Absolutely.

840
00:56:30,920 --> 00:56:33,423
Good.
I think you and--

841
00:56:36,326 --> 00:56:39,162
I think you and Sue Ann
should cover that.

842
00:56:42,665 --> 00:56:45,201
Philippe's voice:
The last time
I saw Sue Ann

843
00:56:45,235 --> 00:56:47,537
she was
a slightly dizzy belle

844
00:56:47,570 --> 00:56:50,073
who I tried to kiss
in the back of a car.

845
00:56:50,106 --> 00:56:54,444
Now she had reincarnated
herself into a journalist.

846
00:56:54,477 --> 00:56:56,713
But then again,
at that age

847
00:56:56,746 --> 00:56:58,481
we tried on
personalities

848
00:56:58,515 --> 00:57:01,017
like other people
try on clothes.

849
00:57:01,050 --> 00:57:03,353
What are you reading?

850
00:59:46,382 --> 00:59:46,783
"Absalom, Absalom!"

851
00:59:46,783 --> 00:59:48,117
Ah, the son of David.

852
00:59:48,151 --> 00:59:49,018
Faulkner.

853
00:59:49,018 --> 01:00:08,871
Look, this conversation
is pointless.

854
01:00:08,872 --> 01:00:09,138
by a kind
of boredom

855
01:00:09,172 --> 01:00:09,405
or embarrassed,
as if he was wondering

856
01:00:09,439 --> 01:00:09,706
what in the world
he was doing

857
01:00:09,706 --> 01:00:31,194
in front of
all these strangers.

858
01:00:31,194 --> 01:00:31,227
He exuded the kind
of suave patience

859
01:00:31,227 --> 01:00:31,494
He spoke
only for the front row

860
01:00:31,494 --> 01:00:31,861
and I doubted
that most of them
even heard him.

861
01:00:31,861 --> 01:00:32,228
But if Faulkner
wanted to whisper,

862
01:00:32,261 --> 01:00:32,629
he'd earned that right
as far as I was concerned.

863
01:00:32,629 --> 01:00:51,180
I'll never forget
that handsome face

864
01:00:51,180 --> 01:00:51,514
his mouth moving
like a sinner

865
01:00:51,547 --> 01:00:51,848
on his deathbed
confession.

866
01:00:51,848 --> 01:00:52,048
I must admit
I'm getting
a little dizzy.

867
01:00:52,081 --> 01:00:52,181
You'll forgive me.

868
01:00:52,749 --> 01:00:52,782
He's--
he's so beautiful.

869
01:01:03,226 --> 01:01:03,326
( laughing )

870
01:01:03,326 --> 01:01:03,359
Sorry.

871
01:01:03,459 --> 01:01:03,893
Sorry.

872
01:01:04,661 --> 01:01:04,961
Look, the only reason
I gave my hand to that girl

873
01:01:04,961 --> 01:01:25,948
is because she is sick.

874
01:01:25,948 --> 01:01:34,957
She's in psychoanalysis.

875
01:01:34,957 --> 01:01:35,291
On your couch?

876
01:01:35,324 --> 01:01:35,625
April, I only love you.

877
01:01:35,658 --> 01:01:35,925
I swear by all
that is sacred to me.

878
01:01:35,958 --> 01:01:36,159
So you're telling me
my eyes are lying?

879
01:01:36,159 --> 01:01:36,626
Your eyes are lying.

880
01:01:36,626 --> 01:01:36,793
No, they're not.

881
01:01:36,793 --> 01:01:36,826
I'll prove it to you.

882
01:02:04,520 --> 01:02:04,554
Well, Hans, what do you think
about the quaint custom
of Thanksgiving?

883
01:02:04,587 --> 01:02:04,787
Thank you, Joanne.
It's wonderful.

884
01:02:04,787 --> 01:02:05,221
It's very nice.

885
01:02:05,221 --> 01:02:05,421
Do you have anything
like it in Austria?

886
01:02:05,421 --> 01:02:05,688
No no.
What is das?

887
01:02:05,688 --> 01:02:05,755
Das is a yam.

888
01:02:05,755 --> 01:02:09,192
How are your
parents, Cal?

889
01:02:09,225 --> 01:02:18,234
They're fine, sir.

890
01:02:18,234 --> 01:02:18,835
Philippe's voice:
You'd think that
of all people

891
01:02:18,835 --> 01:02:19,135
Cal would have
a place to go,
but he didn't.

892
01:02:19,135 --> 01:02:19,402
His parents
were alcoholics

893
01:02:19,669 --> 01:02:21,304
which made him
kind of an orphan himself

894
01:02:21,337 --> 01:02:24,407
and gave him
that edge of sadness

895
01:02:24,440 --> 01:02:27,243
that made him
such a great guy.

896
01:02:27,276 --> 01:02:30,279
Pardon?

897
01:02:30,313 --> 01:02:33,182
Your parents.

898
01:02:33,216 --> 01:02:35,184
You do have parents,
don't you, boy?

899
01:02:35,218 --> 01:02:38,254
Philippe:
Yes, I do have parents.

900
01:03:23,766 --> 01:03:24,367
And they are fine.
I just received a letter
from them

901
01:03:24,367 --> 01:03:24,700
and also
from my brother.

902
01:03:24,967 --> 01:03:25,334
He was a soldier
in the Indochine.

903
01:03:25,334 --> 01:03:25,601
Indochina.

904
01:03:25,668 --> 01:03:26,169
I was in Indochina.

905
01:03:26,169 --> 01:03:26,402
It's a beautiful
country.

906
01:03:26,469 --> 01:03:26,936
Very determined
people,

907
01:03:27,069 --> 01:03:28,271
( door opens )

908
01:03:28,271 --> 01:03:28,771
No, Dominic,
I don't have the magazine

909
01:03:28,771 --> 01:03:41,417
and I don't know
where it is either.

910
01:03:41,417 --> 01:03:41,617
Maybe you should use
your imagination tonight.

911
01:03:41,751 --> 01:03:41,851
What for?

912
01:03:53,029 --> 01:03:56,098
What for?

913
01:03:56,132 --> 01:03:59,235
What's Dominic got to use
his imagination for?

914
01:03:59,268 --> 01:04:03,072
Oh, April,
you are so cruel to me.

915
01:04:03,105 --> 01:04:06,209
Here.

916
01:04:06,242 --> 01:04:08,611
Happy Thanksgiving.

917
01:04:12,148 --> 01:04:14,884
Oh, April.

918
01:04:14,917 --> 01:04:58,794
Thank you, God.

919
01:04:58,794 --> 01:04:58,961
You ever had
pumpkin pie before?

920
01:04:58,961 --> 01:04:59,262
Did you make it?

921
01:05:07,103 --> 01:05:07,303
No.

922
01:05:07,303 --> 01:05:07,637
I'm devouring you.

923
01:05:07,637 --> 01:05:07,937
It is you that I taste.

924
01:05:07,937 --> 01:05:08,204
Your hands
have broken these eggs,

925
01:05:08,204 --> 01:05:08,437
touched this flour
and puréed this--

926
01:05:08,437 --> 01:05:08,471
this most interesting
vegetable.

927
01:05:08,871 --> 01:05:09,071
And you came here
to see me.

928
01:05:09,105 --> 01:05:09,171
Is it not incredibly
dangerous?

929
01:05:09,171 --> 01:05:09,372
No.

930
01:05:09,372 --> 01:05:11,340
It's Thanksgiving.

931
01:05:14,043 --> 01:05:16,078
Forget it.

932
01:05:16,112 --> 01:05:18,080
I'm still angry
with you.

933
01:05:18,114 --> 01:05:22,418
Why?
Because of Sue Ann?

934
01:05:22,451 --> 01:05:24,287
She is so stupid.

935
01:05:24,320 --> 01:05:27,089
I always sleep
with her.

936
01:05:27,123 --> 01:05:30,693
I mean,
when I'm with her

937
01:05:30,726 --> 01:05:33,329
I go to sleep.

938
01:05:33,362 --> 01:05:35,998
She is so boring.

939
01:05:36,032 --> 01:05:38,000
Philippe, I have to
tell you something.

940
01:05:38,034 --> 01:05:41,771
No no, please.

941
01:05:41,804 --> 01:05:43,773
One kiss
for a poor orphan,

942
01:05:43,806 --> 01:05:46,509
all alone
on Thanksgiving.

943
01:05:46,542 --> 01:05:50,112
What's French
for "kiss"?

944
01:05:50,146 --> 01:05:52,782
Bisou.
Un bisou.

945
01:05:52,815 --> 01:05:54,116
That's French
for "kiss"?

946
01:05:54,150 --> 01:05:58,220
Yes, un bisou
is a French kiss.

947
01:05:58,254 --> 01:06:01,657
Well, maybe you'd better
give me one of those.

948
01:06:31,253 --> 01:06:33,289
( Cal cheering )

949
01:06:42,531 --> 01:06:45,401
( Cal cheering )

950
01:06:47,136 --> 01:06:49,505
Hey, Phil.

951
01:06:49,538 --> 01:06:52,174
Phil, let's go for a ride,
little buddy.

952
01:07:04,353 --> 01:07:07,757
Where is everybody?

953
01:07:09,425 --> 01:07:12,294
Oh, I forgot.

954
01:07:12,328 --> 01:07:15,464
With mommy and daddy
for turkey.

955
01:07:18,034 --> 01:07:20,569
Well, fuck all y'all!

956
01:07:23,806 --> 01:07:26,308
'Cause I'm
a Southern belle.

957
01:07:26,342 --> 01:07:28,744
As long as what?

958
01:07:28,778 --> 01:07:31,247
As long as he keeps
winning games.

959
01:07:31,280 --> 01:07:33,249
Thank you, sir.

960
01:07:33,282 --> 01:07:36,352
You're welcome.
Cheers.

961
01:07:36,385 --> 01:07:38,354
( shouting)
Yes, sir!

962
01:07:38,387 --> 01:07:41,257
We're gonna beat
Alabama Tech, sir!

963
01:07:58,040 --> 01:08:00,276
Hey, Phil...

964
01:08:03,079 --> 01:08:05,614
where are you, buddy?

965
01:08:05,648 --> 01:08:08,117
Where is everybody?

966
01:08:53,429 --> 01:08:55,464
Hi, Philippe.

967
01:09:02,538 --> 01:09:05,641
Did you have
a nice Thanksgiving?

968
01:09:05,674 --> 01:09:08,010
Yes.

969
01:09:08,043 --> 01:09:10,513
Yes.
And you?

970
01:09:10,546 --> 01:09:12,982
Did you go back
to Wallatoona?

971
01:09:13,015 --> 01:09:15,484
Wallatoona?

972
01:09:15,518 --> 01:09:17,920
Yes, where you live.

973
01:09:17,953 --> 01:09:20,523
Oh, sure.

974
01:09:23,692 --> 01:09:27,396
It was grand-- grand.

975
01:09:31,100 --> 01:09:33,369
Did you finish
"Catcher in the Rye"?

976
01:09:33,402 --> 01:09:36,105
Yes.

977
01:09:36,138 --> 01:09:38,507
I'm-- I'm gonna see you
this afternoon.

978
01:09:38,541 --> 01:09:41,443
Philippe.
Philippe.

979
01:09:41,477 --> 01:09:44,013
Are you afraid of me?

980
01:09:53,522 --> 01:09:56,659
Philippe's voice:
If only it hadn't rained
that afternoon.

981
01:09:58,727 --> 01:10:02,665
If only I hadn't
sheltered Sue Ann
with my coat.

982
01:10:02,698 --> 01:10:05,668
If only, if only...

983
01:10:12,308 --> 01:10:14,677
Jennings:
"The silhouette
of a moving cat

984
01:10:14,710 --> 01:10:17,813
wavered across
the moonlight,

985
01:10:17,846 --> 01:10:20,349
and turning my head
to watch it,

986
01:10:20,382 --> 01:10:23,619
I saw that
I was not alone--

987
01:10:23,652 --> 01:10:26,055
fifty feet away
a figure had emerged

988
01:10:26,088 --> 01:10:27,990
from the shadow
of my neighbor's mansion

989
01:10:28,023 --> 01:10:31,527
and was standing
with his hands
in his pockets

990
01:10:31,560 --> 01:10:33,963
regarding
the silver pepper

991
01:10:33,996 --> 01:10:36,899
of the stars.

992
01:10:36,932 --> 01:10:39,201
Something in his
leisurely movements

993
01:10:39,235 --> 01:10:42,071
and the secure position
of his feet upon the lawn

994
01:10:42,104 --> 01:10:46,875
suggested that it was
Mr. Gatsby himself,

995
01:10:46,909 --> 01:10:50,846
come out to determine
what share was his

996
01:10:50,879 --> 01:10:54,450
of our local heavens."

997
01:10:54,483 --> 01:10:58,087
We don't seem to be
holding your attention,
Mr. Cate.

998
01:11:01,457 --> 01:11:04,460
Well, it's just a bunch
of Yankee talk to me.

999
01:11:04,493 --> 01:11:06,929
Oh, it's just
a bunch of Yankee talk?

1000
01:11:06,962 --> 01:11:09,765
What do you think,
Philippe?

1001
01:11:13,202 --> 01:11:14,737
Pardon?

1002
01:11:14,770 --> 01:11:17,339
You'll have to excuse
our French friend
today, sir.

1003
01:11:17,373 --> 01:11:20,075
See, it's my
considered opinion

1004
01:11:20,109 --> 01:11:22,011
that his mind is
on other things.

1005
01:11:24,246 --> 01:11:27,082
Oh, all right.

1006
01:11:27,116 --> 01:11:29,184
Let us move on
to matters

1007
01:11:29,218 --> 01:11:32,354
less controversial
then, shall we?

1008
01:11:32,388 --> 01:11:34,657
Something romantic?

1009
01:11:34,690 --> 01:11:36,925
Romantic?

1010
01:11:38,727 --> 01:11:41,297
Romantic.

1011
01:11:41,330 --> 01:11:43,432
Ah, here we go.

1012
01:11:43,465 --> 01:11:46,201
Lord Byron.

1013
01:11:46,235 --> 01:11:49,471
Ooh, mad, bad
and dangerous to know.

1014
01:11:49,505 --> 01:11:51,840
Yeah, you identify
with that, don't you, Cal?

1015
01:11:51,874 --> 01:11:54,576
It's my family's
motto, sir.

1016
01:11:54,610 --> 01:11:56,945
I'm sure it is.
Now...

1017
01:11:59,348 --> 01:12:02,151
- this here poem...
- ( door slams )

1018
01:12:02,184 --> 01:12:04,920
...is called
"When We Two Parted."

1019
01:12:07,122 --> 01:12:10,159
Excuse me.

1020
01:12:10,192 --> 01:12:12,261
You know
where it is by now.

1021
01:12:19,535 --> 01:12:22,204
Does anybody have
anything else

1022
01:12:22,237 --> 01:12:24,640
that they need to do
before we begin?

1023
01:12:25,908 --> 01:12:29,111
No?
Good.

1024
01:12:29,144 --> 01:12:31,113
This is a story

1025
01:12:31,146 --> 01:12:33,115
of a passionate
love affair...

1026
01:12:33,148 --> 01:12:36,552
- April.
- ...come to a painful
and premature end.

1027
01:12:50,132 --> 01:12:52,801
"When we two parted

1028
01:12:52,835 --> 01:12:55,604
In silence and tears,

1029
01:12:55,637 --> 01:12:58,307
Half broken-hearted

1030
01:12:58,340 --> 01:13:01,009
To sever for years,

1031
01:13:01,043 --> 01:13:04,780
Pale grew thy cheek
and cold,

1032
01:13:04,813 --> 01:13:07,316
Colder thy kiss;

1033
01:13:07,349 --> 01:13:10,119
Truly that hour foretold

1034
01:13:10,152 --> 01:13:12,121
Sorrow to this."

1035
01:13:12,154 --> 01:13:15,057
Go away.

1036
01:13:15,090 --> 01:13:17,059
"The dew of the morning

1037
01:13:17,092 --> 01:13:19,728
Sunk chill on my brow--

1038
01:13:19,762 --> 01:13:21,730
It felt like the warning

1039
01:13:21,764 --> 01:13:25,000
Of what I feel now.

1040
01:13:25,033 --> 01:13:28,370
Thy vows are all broken,

1041
01:13:28,404 --> 01:13:30,973
And light is thy fame:

1042
01:13:31,006 --> 01:13:33,409
I hear thy name spoken,

1043
01:13:33,442 --> 01:13:35,811
And share in its shame."

1044
01:13:36,979 --> 01:13:38,614
- Mrs. Jennings: April.
- Yes, ma'am.

1045
01:13:38,647 --> 01:13:40,482
Where is
that green bowl?

1046
01:13:40,516 --> 01:13:43,519
Jennings:
Honey, for crying out loud,
I'm trying to read here.

1047
01:13:43,552 --> 01:13:45,754
Mrs. Jennings:
I'm sorry.

1048
01:13:48,090 --> 01:13:50,292
"They name thee
before me,

1049
01:13:50,325 --> 01:13:53,061
A knell
to mine ear;

1050
01:13:53,095 --> 01:13:55,364
A shadow
comes o'er me--

1051
01:13:55,397 --> 01:13:59,168
Why wert thou
so dear?

1052
01:13:59,201 --> 01:14:01,603
They know not
I knew thee,

1053
01:14:01,637 --> 01:14:04,506
Who knew thee
too well:

1054
01:14:04,540 --> 01:14:07,776
Long, long
shall I rue thee,

1055
01:14:07,810 --> 01:14:11,547
Too deeply to tell.

1056
01:14:11,580 --> 01:14:14,550
Jennings and April:
In secret we met--

1057
01:14:14,583 --> 01:14:18,554
In silence
I grieve,

1058
01:14:18,587 --> 01:14:21,457
That thy heart
could forget,

1059
01:14:21,490 --> 01:14:24,593
Thy spirit deceive.

1060
01:14:24,626 --> 01:14:27,296
If I should
meet thee

1061
01:14:27,329 --> 01:14:29,898
After long years,

1062
01:14:29,932 --> 01:14:32,935
How should I
greet thee?

1063
01:14:32,968 --> 01:14:36,238
With silence
and tears."

1064
01:14:49,117 --> 01:14:51,753
You two
know each other?

1065
01:14:51,787 --> 01:14:53,755
No, we don't.

1066
01:14:53,789 --> 01:14:56,258
I need
that green bowl.

1067
01:15:04,032 --> 01:15:07,169
Jennings:
Now this poem
was published in 1816--

1068
01:15:07,202 --> 01:15:10,038
the same year
that Byron left England,
never to return.

1069
01:15:10,072 --> 01:15:12,908
He was, as I'm sure
you recall,

1070
01:15:12,941 --> 01:15:15,277
divorced
rather scandalously,

1071
01:15:15,310 --> 01:15:17,646
so this was probably
a goodbye

1072
01:15:17,679 --> 01:15:20,082
to some forbidden lover.

1073
01:15:22,584 --> 01:15:24,553
Well, Phil,
all I can say is

1074
01:15:24,586 --> 01:15:27,089
you missed
one hell of a poem.

1075
01:15:28,824 --> 01:15:30,859
Philippe's voice:
I looked for my April,

1076
01:15:30,893 --> 01:15:33,295
but she vanished
in December.

1077
01:15:33,328 --> 01:15:36,298
She left her job
at the Jenningses

1078
01:15:36,331 --> 01:15:39,735
and the Baptist minister
hadn't seen her either.

1079
01:15:44,072 --> 01:15:46,308
Hey, bubi,
want to play?

1080
01:15:55,984 --> 01:15:58,420
Good.
( muttering )

1081
01:16:05,627 --> 01:16:07,696
Argh!

1082
01:16:07,729 --> 01:16:09,798
Hans:
Good. Wunderbar.

1083
01:16:11,667 --> 01:16:14,403
( all grunting )

1084
01:16:24,613 --> 01:16:27,015
All right,
right here, Mr. Cate.

1085
01:16:27,049 --> 01:16:29,084
Here you go.

1086
01:16:31,553 --> 01:16:33,522
All right,
now go easy, Hoss.

1087
01:16:33,555 --> 01:16:36,158
It's consistency
we're looking for.
Capisci?

1088
01:16:38,393 --> 01:16:40,095
Great shot!

1089
01:16:42,097 --> 01:16:44,566
Do it again.

1090
01:16:56,612 --> 01:16:58,580
( growling )

1091
01:16:58,614 --> 01:17:02,918
Hey! Hey!

1092
01:17:02,951 --> 01:17:05,153
Hike.

1093
01:17:05,187 --> 01:17:07,556
( grunts )

1094
01:17:11,093 --> 01:17:15,130
Philippe.
Hey, Philippe.

1095
01:17:15,163 --> 01:17:17,699
Run, boy, run!
Put some heat
under it.

1096
01:17:20,435 --> 01:17:22,270
Let me ask you
a question--

1097
01:17:22,304 --> 01:17:26,141
you think you can do that
with 11 assholes
from Alabama Tech

1098
01:17:26,174 --> 01:17:28,143
looking to rip
your leg off?

1099
01:17:28,176 --> 01:17:30,212
I can do it with my
left foot too.

1100
01:17:31,847 --> 01:17:34,583
Okay, go get yourself
a number.

1101
01:17:34,616 --> 01:17:36,885
Pardon?

1102
01:17:36,918 --> 01:17:38,854
You just made
the team, Frenchy.

1103
01:17:38,887 --> 01:17:41,289
Go on.
Go on.

1104
01:17:46,495 --> 01:17:48,463
( cheering )

1105
01:17:48,497 --> 01:17:50,666
Yeah, Frenchy,
you made the team!

1106
01:17:51,767 --> 01:17:54,636
Anyway, listen,
this alumni says to me,

1107
01:17:54,670 --> 01:17:56,872
he says, "Hey, Cal,
if you beat Alabama Tech

1108
01:17:56,905 --> 01:17:59,174
you got yourself
a brand new Caddy...

1109
01:17:59,207 --> 01:18:01,343
convertible."

1110
01:18:03,578 --> 01:18:06,314
Hi, Cal.
Hi, Philippe.

1111
01:18:12,621 --> 01:18:14,122
Hi, Sue Ann.

1112
01:18:23,131 --> 01:18:25,200
There's a girl
to see you.

1113
01:18:25,233 --> 01:18:28,036
She's downstairs.

1114
01:18:28,070 --> 01:18:29,905
April.

1115
01:18:38,380 --> 01:18:42,184
I came
to say goodbye.

1116
01:18:42,217 --> 01:18:44,553
John Patrick Baldridge,

1117
01:18:44,586 --> 01:18:46,688
Elizabeth's father.

1118
01:18:46,722 --> 01:18:49,725
I told them
you were a Marquis.

1119
01:18:49,758 --> 01:18:51,727
Elizabeth?

1120
01:18:51,760 --> 01:18:53,729
Oh, monsieur,

1121
01:18:53,762 --> 01:18:56,431
we're taking our daughter
back to Boston.

1122
01:18:56,465 --> 01:18:58,533
Much to our surprise,
we find

1123
01:18:58,567 --> 01:19:00,836
that she is
seriously ill.

1124
01:19:00,869 --> 01:19:02,170
Ill?

1125
01:19:02,204 --> 01:19:05,107
Oh, the unspeakable things
she's been reading.

1126
01:19:06,675 --> 01:19:10,145
He has

1127
01:19:10,178 --> 01:19:16,084
a black mistress.

1128
01:19:17,652 --> 01:19:19,621
Mr. Baldridge:
As you see,
Monsieur le Marquis,

1129
01:19:19,654 --> 01:19:22,891
she is really
very ill.

1130
01:19:22,924 --> 01:19:26,194
Yes, I can see that.

1131
01:19:26,228 --> 01:19:28,897
Mrs. Baldridge:
She is incapable
of meeting

1132
01:19:28,930 --> 01:19:31,967
the challenges
awaiting her--

1133
01:19:32,000 --> 01:19:34,336
challenges we have devoted
all of our love

1134
01:19:34,369 --> 01:19:36,638
and experience
to prepare her for.

1135
01:19:36,671 --> 01:19:39,074
Love?

1136
01:19:39,107 --> 01:19:41,743
Mommy,

1137
01:19:41,777 --> 01:19:44,746
did you say love?

1138
01:19:44,780 --> 01:19:46,615
( laughing )
Love?

1139
01:19:46,648 --> 01:19:50,318
Philippe's voice:
My God, her name was
Elizabeth, not Sue Ann--

1140
01:19:50,352 --> 01:19:53,755
just another square peg
trying to fit into
a round hole

1141
01:19:53,789 --> 01:19:57,492
till there was
nothing left of her
but splinters.

1142
01:20:00,462 --> 01:20:02,831
Philippe:
Excuse me.

1143
01:20:04,132 --> 01:20:06,635
I haven't seen her.

1144
01:20:06,668 --> 01:20:08,970
I know, I know,

1145
01:20:09,004 --> 01:20:11,039
but just the smallest
of messages...

1146
01:20:11,072 --> 01:20:15,076
I can't do that.
Now I can only guess
at your relationship.

1147
01:20:15,110 --> 01:20:17,078
Not only is it wrong
in the eyes of God,

1148
01:20:17,112 --> 01:20:19,181
but, son,
it's dangerous.

1149
01:20:19,214 --> 01:20:21,183
I know.

1150
01:20:21,216 --> 01:20:23,185
Yes, you're right,
I'm sure,

1151
01:20:23,218 --> 01:20:25,187
but if you could
just tell her

1152
01:20:25,220 --> 01:20:27,522
that I'm playing against
Alabama Tech tomorrow.

1153
01:20:27,556 --> 01:20:29,991
You?
Oh, dear Lord, help us.

1154
01:20:30,025 --> 01:20:32,928
I'm just a kicker.
But please please,

1155
01:20:32,961 --> 01:20:34,930
after this game
my semester is over

1156
01:20:34,963 --> 01:20:37,899
and I have to go
back to Paris.

1157
01:20:41,369 --> 01:20:43,772
Hey, son,
kick some 'Bama butt.

1158
01:20:47,309 --> 01:20:50,345
( cheering )

1159
01:20:50,378 --> 01:20:53,782
33 red on two.
One, two, ready?

1160
01:20:53,815 --> 01:20:56,151
What the hell?

1161
01:20:56,184 --> 01:20:58,153
He's calling
his own damn play!

1162
01:20:58,186 --> 01:21:00,055
He's calling his own
play out there!

1163
01:21:00,055 --> 01:21:01,122
( grunting )

1164
01:21:01,156 --> 01:21:03,692
Cover me, cover me,
cover me.

1165
01:21:08,230 --> 01:21:10,432
( crowd booing,
whistle blows )

1166
01:21:10,465 --> 01:21:11,967
( players cheering )

1167
01:21:13,134 --> 01:21:15,103
All right, you bunch
of candy asses,

1168
01:21:15,136 --> 01:21:17,439
get your butts
over here and listen up.
And I mean now.

1169
01:21:17,472 --> 01:21:19,507
Move it, move it.

1170
01:21:21,009 --> 01:21:22,978
Boys, what do you
think's gonna happen

1171
01:21:23,011 --> 01:21:25,914
if we don't win this
football game, huh?

1172
01:21:25,947 --> 01:21:28,683
Nothing.

1173
01:21:28,717 --> 01:21:33,088
Well, you'll be
disappointed,

1174
01:21:33,121 --> 01:21:37,292
but then you'll go home
for Christmas.

1175
01:21:37,325 --> 01:21:40,629
But for me
and my wife,

1176
01:21:40,662 --> 01:21:42,631
my boy Cody

1177
01:21:42,664 --> 01:21:45,500
and my little
Elizabeth--

1178
01:21:45,533 --> 01:21:49,271
we're not gonna have
any Christmas.

1179
01:21:49,304 --> 01:21:52,107
They're gonna fire
my ass.

1180
01:21:52,140 --> 01:21:54,509
Yes, sir.

1181
01:21:54,542 --> 01:21:57,212
So while you're

1182
01:21:57,245 --> 01:21:59,547
around your
Christmas tree,

1183
01:21:59,581 --> 01:22:01,349
opening your presents
with your family,

1184
01:22:01,383 --> 01:22:03,351
I'm gonna be trying
to explain to Cody

1185
01:22:03,385 --> 01:22:05,854
why he's not gonna
get that bicycle

1186
01:22:05,887 --> 01:22:08,390
he's counted on
all year

1187
01:22:08,423 --> 01:22:10,959
and why there's a sign
in our front yard

1188
01:22:10,992 --> 01:22:12,961
that says "For Sale"

1189
01:22:12,994 --> 01:22:16,231
instead of a snowman.

1190
01:22:16,264 --> 01:22:18,233
Jane and I will be
packing up

1191
01:22:18,266 --> 01:22:20,235
the last couple
of crates

1192
01:22:20,268 --> 01:22:22,470
and my little girl's gonna
come down the stairs

1193
01:22:22,504 --> 01:22:24,139
in her jammies
and she's gonna say to me,

1194
01:22:24,172 --> 01:22:30,045
"Daddy, why do we
have to leave?

1195
01:22:30,078 --> 01:22:32,080
Boys, I'm gonna
tell her the truth

1196
01:22:32,113 --> 01:22:34,082
like I always do.

1197
01:22:34,115 --> 01:22:36,084
I'm gonna say to her,
"Darling,

1198
01:22:36,117 --> 01:22:38,653
there was a group
of young men,

1199
01:22:38,687 --> 01:22:41,456
fine young men,
brave young men,

1200
01:22:41,489 --> 01:22:44,826
talented young men
who when the chips
were down--

1201
01:22:44,859 --> 01:22:47,996
they just threw in
the towel.

1202
01:22:48,029 --> 01:22:50,932
And the shame is,

1203
01:22:50,966 --> 01:22:53,468
they were good.

1204
01:22:53,501 --> 01:22:55,470
I mean, they were
real good.

1205
01:22:55,503 --> 01:22:57,539
They were this close
to being the very best,

1206
01:22:57,572 --> 01:23:00,175
but they threw in
the goddamn towel."

1207
01:23:10,852 --> 01:23:13,355
Let's kill
the bastards!

1208
01:23:13,388 --> 01:23:15,357
Philippe's voice:
Much later I learned

1209
01:23:15,390 --> 01:23:18,326
that Coach Mallard was
and always had been

1210
01:23:18,360 --> 01:23:20,328
a confirmed
bachelor.

1211
01:23:20,362 --> 01:23:22,564
( band playing,
crowd cheering )

1212
01:23:32,507 --> 01:23:35,910
Announcer:
And now they're coming back
for the second half.

1213
01:23:35,944 --> 01:23:39,748
So let's hear it
for the ASU Rebels!

1214
01:23:51,059 --> 01:23:53,028
Anybody lays a hand
on him,

1215
01:23:53,061 --> 01:23:55,497
and you're gonna be
the new altar boy.
You understand me?

1216
01:23:55,530 --> 01:23:57,365
Now you get out there
and you tear it up.

1217
01:23:57,399 --> 01:23:58,566
Go go go!

1218
01:24:14,282 --> 01:24:16,284
Announcer:
It's third down
and nine to go.

1219
01:24:16,317 --> 01:24:18,319
Can they do it?

1220
01:24:21,389 --> 01:24:23,091
Jack's open, coach.

1221
01:24:23,124 --> 01:24:24,626
It's third down.
We're running it.

1222
01:24:24,659 --> 01:24:26,561
Come on, coach.
It's wide open.

1223
01:24:26,594 --> 01:24:29,164
I can get it there.
Just trust me.

1224
01:24:29,197 --> 01:24:31,533
Okay, call your own
damn play.

1225
01:24:34,469 --> 01:24:38,740
Philippe.
Hey, Frenchy, come here.

1226
01:24:38,773 --> 01:24:40,742
How are you feeling,
Frenchy?

1227
01:24:40,775 --> 01:24:42,577
- Fine.
- That's good.

1228
01:24:42,610 --> 01:24:45,513
Down, set, hut!

1229
01:24:49,584 --> 01:24:52,287
( whistle blows )

1230
01:24:54,689 --> 01:24:57,258
Time out.
Time out.

1231
01:24:57,292 --> 01:25:00,128
Kid, let's see
what you're made of.

1232
01:25:01,863 --> 01:25:04,632
Announcer:
And with only
seconds to go,

1233
01:25:04,666 --> 01:25:07,035
they're bringing on
their ace in the hole

1234
01:25:07,068 --> 01:25:09,671
Philippe Leclerc
to try for the field goal.

1235
01:25:13,174 --> 01:25:14,642
You got it.
Good luck.

1236
01:25:21,583 --> 01:25:23,852
Save my ass, buddy.

1237
01:25:30,091 --> 01:25:31,626
Time out.
Time out.

1238
01:25:31,659 --> 01:25:33,628
( whistle blows,
players groaning )

1239
01:25:33,661 --> 01:25:36,197
Player:
Bring it in.
Bring it in.

1240
01:25:38,700 --> 01:25:40,902
Another time out?

1241
01:25:41,903 --> 01:25:44,672
They want you
to think about it, Hoss.

1242
01:25:44,706 --> 01:25:48,209
What's there
to think about?

1243
01:25:48,243 --> 01:25:50,612
( players cheering )

1244
01:25:54,282 --> 01:25:57,285
Long enough
for my man here
to take a shot.

1245
01:26:17,305 --> 01:26:19,707
( rapid heartbeat )

1246
01:26:19,741 --> 01:26:21,876
( whistle blows )
Base.

1247
01:26:25,280 --> 01:26:27,315
Cal:
Hut hut!

1248
01:26:29,817 --> 01:26:32,187
Frenchy!

1249
01:26:32,220 --> 01:26:34,255
Throw the ball!

1250
01:26:35,890 --> 01:26:37,892
Frenchy!

1251
01:26:39,060 --> 01:26:41,896
Throw the ball!

1252
01:26:41,930 --> 01:26:44,098
Frenchy, throw it,
throw it!

1253
01:26:44,132 --> 01:26:45,867
Frenchy, throw the ball!

1254
01:26:45,900 --> 01:26:48,136
Throw it, throw it!

1255
01:26:53,474 --> 01:26:55,643
( cheering )

1256
01:26:55,677 --> 01:26:57,745
( band playing )

1257
01:27:10,925 --> 01:27:12,927
April!

1258
01:27:13,995 --> 01:27:15,997
Put me down.

1259
01:27:18,800 --> 01:27:23,004
Philippe's voice:
This time she was
truly gone.

1260
01:27:23,037 --> 01:27:25,006
And at the end
of the day,

1261
01:27:25,039 --> 01:27:27,108
it wasn't
because of Sue Ann

1262
01:27:27,141 --> 01:27:29,477
or even the fact
that I was a student

1263
01:27:29,510 --> 01:27:32,013
and she a maid, no.

1264
01:27:32,046 --> 01:27:35,149
We'd been thrown together
for a brief moment

1265
01:27:35,183 --> 01:27:37,719
two foreigners
traveling side by side

1266
01:27:37,752 --> 01:27:39,721
through this great
and strange land

1267
01:27:39,754 --> 01:27:41,956
called America.

1268
01:27:41,990 --> 01:27:44,525
( dance music playing )

1269
01:27:44,559 --> 01:27:46,794
But all I had to do
to be accepted

1270
01:27:46,828 --> 01:27:49,230
was to win
a football game.

1271
01:27:49,264 --> 01:27:53,301
For April it wasn't
quite that easy.

1272
01:27:53,334 --> 01:27:55,303
Congratulations.

1273
01:27:55,336 --> 01:27:57,639
You were exhilarating
out there today.

1274
01:27:57,672 --> 01:27:59,641
I didn't know
you had it in you.

1275
01:27:59,674 --> 01:28:01,743
You have ice water
in your veins, son,
ice water.

1276
01:28:01,776 --> 01:28:03,745
Thank you.

1277
01:28:03,778 --> 01:28:06,581
( girls giggling )
Come on, Cal.

1278
01:28:06,614 --> 01:28:09,684
( Cal laughing )
Okay, hey, easy.
One at a time, girls.

1279
01:28:09,717 --> 01:28:11,085
Cal.

1280
01:28:11,119 --> 01:28:14,322
Hey, whoa, easy.

1281
01:28:16,157 --> 01:28:19,761
Philippe:
Now, almost
40 years later,

1282
01:28:19,794 --> 01:28:21,763
I've come to realize

1283
01:28:21,796 --> 01:28:25,199
that youth is a gift
wasted on the young.

1284
01:28:25,233 --> 01:28:27,835
I was too preoccupied
with my role

1285
01:28:27,869 --> 01:28:30,772
as the Hamlet
of the freshman dorm

1286
01:28:30,805 --> 01:28:34,075
to truly appreciate
the friends I made

1287
01:28:34,108 --> 01:28:37,879
in that semester
in the Shenandoah Valley.

1288
01:28:37,912 --> 01:28:40,581
Somehow I wasn't quite

1289
01:28:40,615 --> 01:28:43,418
up to the grandeur
of Cal Cate,

1290
01:28:43,451 --> 01:28:45,920
the poetry
of Zach,

1291
01:28:45,953 --> 01:28:48,489
the tragedy
of Sue Ann

1292
01:28:48,523 --> 01:28:50,491
and, most of all,

1293
01:28:50,525 --> 01:28:53,161
the passion
of April.

1294
01:28:53,194 --> 01:28:56,464
And now,
like so many men

